@{
    ViewData["Title"] = "The Server in Web Communication";
}

<body data-topic="web-communication-server">
<div class="container">
    <h1 class="text-center">What is a Server in Web Communication?</h1>

    <div class="beginner-note">
        <div class="beginner-note-icon">
            <i class="fas fa-server"></i>
        </div>
        <div class="beginner-note-content">
            <h4>Think of the Server Like a Kitchen in a Restaurant</h4>
            <p><strong>Server = Kitchen</strong> that prepares and serves food to customers</p>
            <p><strong>Simple analogy:</strong></p>
            <ul>
                <li>Kitchen (Server) receives orders from customers</li>
                <li>Chefs prepare the food according to the order</li>
                <li>Kitchen sends the prepared food back to customers</li>
                <li>Kitchen can handle many customers at once</li>
            </ul>
            <p><strong>In web terms:</strong> The server receives requests, processes them, and sends back responses!</p>
        </div>
    </div>

    <div class="intro-section">
        <p>A <strong>server</strong> is a powerful computer (or group of computers) that stores websites, applications, and data, and delivers them to clients upon request. It's like a <strong>giant digital kitchen</strong> that serves information!</p>
        
        <div class="alert alert-info">
            <i class="fas fa-lightbulb"></i> <strong>Quick Definition:</strong> A server is <strong>ANYTHING that provides information or services</strong> when asked.
        </div>
    </div>

    <h2 class="text-center">Everyday Examples of Servers</h2>
    
    <div class="examples-section">
        <div class="example-item">
            <h4><i class="fas fa-search"></i> Google's Servers</h4>
            <p><strong>What they do:</strong> Store billions of web pages and search results</p>
            <p><strong>When you use:</strong> Google Search, Google Maps, YouTube, Gmail</p>
            <p><strong>Response time:</strong> Answers your search in less than 0.5 seconds!</p>
        </div>
        
        <div class="example-item">
            <h4><i class="fas fa-film"></i> Netflix's Servers</h4>
            <p><strong>What they do:</strong> Store thousands of movies and TV shows</p>
            <p><strong>When you use:</strong> Watching Stranger Things or any Netflix show</p>
            <p><strong>Response time:</strong> Streams video instantly to your device</p>
        </div>
        
        <div class="example-item">
            <h4><i class="fas fa-shopping-cart"></i> Amazon's Servers</h4>
            <p><strong>What they do:</strong> Store product information, prices, user accounts</p>
            <p><strong>When you use:</strong> Shopping on Amazon website or app</p>
            <p><strong>Response time:</strong> Shows products and processes orders instantly</p>
        </div>
        
        <div class="example-item">
            <h4><i class="fas fa-gamepad"></i> Gaming Servers</h4>
            <p><strong>What they do:</strong> Host online games and track player progress</p>
            <p><strong>When you use:</strong> Playing Fortnite, Minecraft Online, Call of Duty</p>
            <p><strong>Response time:</strong> Updates game state for all players simultaneously</p>
        </div>
    </div>

    <h2 class="text-center">How Servers Work - Simple Step-by-Step</h2>
    
    <div class="visual-section">
        <div class="server-diagram">
            <div class="server-step">
                <div class="server-icon">
                    <i class="fas fa-envelope"></i>
                </div>
                <div class="server-content">
                    <h5>1. Receives Request</h5>
                    <p>Server gets a message: "Client wants Facebook homepage"</p>
                </div>
            </div>
            
            <div class="server-arrow">
                <i class="fas fa-arrow-right"></i>
            </div>
            
            <div class="server-step">
                <div class="server-icon">
                    <i class="fas fa-cogs"></i>
                </div>
                <div class="server-content">
                    <h5>2. Processes Request</h5>
                    <p>Server finds the Facebook homepage files and prepares them</p>
                </div>
            </div>
            
            <div class="server-arrow">
                <i class="fas fa-arrow-right"></i>
            </div>
            
            <div class="server-step">
                <div class="server-icon">
                    <i class="fas fa-truck"></i>
                </div>
                <div class="server-content">
                    <h5>3. Sends Response</h5>
                    <p>Server sends back: "Here's the Facebook homepage you requested"</p>
                </div>
            </div>
            
            <div class="server-arrow">
                <i class="fas fa-arrow-right"></i>
            </div>
            
            <div class="server-step">
                <div class="server-icon">
                    <i class="fas fa-redo"></i>
                </div>
                <div class="server-content">
                    <h5>4. Waits for Next</h5>
                    <p>Server goes back to waiting for the next request</p>
                </div>
            </div>
        </div>
    </div>

    <h2 class="text-center">Types of Servers - What They Serve</h2>
    
    <div class="comparison-table">
        <table class="table">
            <thead>
                <tr>
                    <th>Type of Server</th>
                    <th>Serves...</th>
                    <th>Real Example</th>
                </tr>
            </thead>
            <tbody>
                <tr>
                    <td><strong>Web Server</strong></td>
                    <td>Websites and web pages</td>
                    <td>Apache, Nginx - serves HTML, CSS, JavaScript</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                    <td><strong>Database Server</strong></td>
                    <td>Stored data and information</td>
                    <td>MySQL, PostgreSQL - stores user accounts, products</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                    <td><strong>File Server</strong></td>
                    <td>Files and documents</td>
                    <td>Google Drive, Dropbox - stores and shares files</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                    <td><strong>Game Server</strong></td>
                    <td>Online multiplayer games</td>
                    <td>Steam servers, PlayStation Network</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                    <td><strong>Mail Server</strong></td>
                    <td>Emails and messages</td>
                    <td>Gmail servers, Outlook servers</td>
                </tr>
            </tbody>
        </table>
    </div>

    <div class="code-container">
        <div class="code-header">Real Example: What a Server Actually Sends Back</div>
        <div class="code-content">
<pre><code class="language-http">
HTTP/1.1 200 OK
Content-Type: text/html; charset=UTF-8
Content-Length: 1256
Server: Apache/2.4.41
Date: Mon, 15 Jan 2024 10:30:00 GMT

&lt;!DOCTYPE html&gt;
&lt;html&gt;
&lt;head&gt;
    &lt;title&gt;Facebook - Log In or Sign Up&lt;/title&gt;
&lt;/head&gt;
&lt;body&gt;
    &lt;h1&gt;Welcome to Facebook&lt;/h1&gt;
    &lt;!-- More HTML code here --&gt;
&lt;/body&gt;
&lt;/html&gt;
</code></pre>
        </div>
        <div class="code-explanation">
            <p><strong>This is what Facebook's server sends back:</strong></p>
            <ol>
                <li><code>200 OK</code> = "Success! Here's what you asked for"</li>
                <li><code>Content-Type: text/html</code> = "This is an HTML webpage"</li>
                <li><code>Content-Length: 1256</code> = "The webpage is 1256 characters long"</li>
                <li><code>Server: Apache</code> = "I'm using Apache server software"</li>
                <li>The HTML code is the actual Facebook homepage</li>
            </ol>
        </div>
    </div>

    <h2 class="text-center">Server Superpowers</h2>
    
    <div class="superpowers-section">
        <div class="superpower">
            <div class="superpower-icon">
                <i class="fas fa-bolt"></i>
            </div>
            <div class="superpower-content">
                <h4>Always Awake</h4>
                <p>Servers run 24/7/365 - never sleep, never take breaks!</p>
            </div>
        </div>
        
        <div class="superpower">
            <div class="superpower-icon">
                <i class="fas fa-users"></i>
            </div>
            <div class="superpower-content">
                <h4>Multi-tasking Master</h4>
                <p>Can handle thousands of requests at the same time</p>
            </div>
        </div>
        
        <div class="superpower">
            <div class="superpower-icon">
                <i class="fas fa-shield-alt"></i>
            </div>
            <div class="superpower-content">
                <h4>Security Guard</h4>
                <p>Protects data and checks who's allowed to access what</p>
            </div>
        </div>
        
        <div class="superpower">
            <div class="superpower-icon">
                <i class="fas fa-database"></i>
            </div>
            <div class="superpower-content">
                <h4>Memory Champion</h4>
                <p>Stores massive amounts of data and remembers everything</p>
            </div>
        </div>
    </div>

    <div class="interactive-example">
        <h3><i class="fas fa-hand-pointer"></i> Try It Yourself: Be the Server!</h3>
        <div class="interactive-content">
            <p>Imagine you're a web server. What would you do in these situations?</p>
            
            <div class="scenario">
                <p><strong>Scenario 1:</strong> A client asks for "youtube.com/watch?v=cats"</p>
                <div class="options">
                    <button class="btn btn-outline-secondary option-btn" data-correct="true">Find the cat video file and send it back</button>
                    <button class="btn btn-outline-secondary option-btn" data-correct="false">Send them yesterday's weather report</button>
                    <button class="btn btn-outline-secondary option-btn" data-correct="false">Ask them for their credit card number</button>
                </div>
            </div>
            
            <div class="scenario">
                <p><strong>Scenario 2:</strong> A client asks for "gmail.com/inbox" but isn't logged in</p>
                <div class="options">
                    <button class="btn btn-outline-secondary option-btn" data-correct="true">Send them the login page instead</button>
                    <button class="btn btn-outline-secondary option-btn" data-correct="false">Send them someone else's emails</button>
                    <button class="btn btn-outline-secondary option-btn" data-correct="false">Ignore the request completely</button>
                </div>
            </div>
            
            <div class="scenario">
                <p><strong>Scenario 3:</strong> A client asks for "amazon.com/product/123" but product doesn't exist</p>
                <div class="options">
                    <button class="btn btn-outline-secondary option-btn" data-correct="false">Send them a random product</button>
                    <button class="btn btn-outline-secondary option-btn" data-correct="true">Send "404 Not Found" error page</button>
                    <button class="btn btn-outline-secondary option-btn" data-correct="false">Crash and stop working</button>
                </div>
            </div>
        </div>
    </div>

    <div class="real-world-analogy">
        <h3><i class="fas fa-store"></i> Real-World Analogy: Server Farm</h3>
        <div class="analogy-content">
            <p><strong>Think of servers like a huge warehouse:</strong></p>
            <div class="analogy-comparison">
                <div class="analogy-item">
                    <h5>Warehouse (Server)</h5>
                    <ul>
                        <li>Stores all the products (data)</li>
                        <li>Has shelves organized by category</li>
                        <li>Workers (server programs) fetch items</li>
                        <li>Packages items for delivery</li>
                    </ul>
                </div>
                <div class="analogy-item">
                    <h5>Delivery (Network)</h5>
                    <ul>
                        <li>Trucks (internet) transport packages</li>
                        <li>Fast delivery systems (fiber optics)</li>
                        <li>Multiple routes available</li>
                        <li>Sometimes traffic (slow internet)</li>
                    </ul>
                </div>
                <div class="analogy-item">
                    <h5>Customer (Client)</h5>
                    <ul>
                        <li>Orders items online</li>
                        <li>Waits for delivery</li>
                        <li>Unboxes and uses items</li>
                        <li>Can return items (send data back)</li>
                    </ul>
                </div>
            </div>
        </div>
    </div>

    <div class="key-points">
        <h3>Key Points to Remember</h3>
        <ul>
            <li><strong>Server = Service Provider</strong> - Gives information when asked</li>
            <li><strong>Always available</strong> - Runs 24/7 to serve requests anytime</li>
            <li><strong>Powerful computers</strong> - Much stronger than your laptop/phone</li>
            <li><strong>Different types:</strong> Web servers, database servers, file servers</li>
            <li><strong>Processes requests:</strong> Finds, prepares, and sends back data</li>
            <li><strong>Manages resources:</strong> Handles many users at once efficiently</li>
        </ul>
    </div>

    <div class="navigation-buttons">
        <a href="@Url.Action("Client", "WebCommunication")" class="btn btn-outline-primary ajax-link">← What is a Client?</a>
        <a href="@Url.Action("Browser", "WebCommunication")" class="btn btn-primary ajax-link">Next: What is a Browser? →</a>
    </div>
</div>

